re: performance issue, I'm not very familiar with cmake, but just to be sure, is libghostty being built in release mode? In debug mode it can be very slow due to the numerous asserts. I tried making a zig implementation of this before and got fairly far, but I racked my brain for days about the performance until I realized that switching to release build fixed it 4258b36739163760fd6fee3c951ad2cd480662bc

@justinmk I tried your commands in my implementation, and it was perfectly fine even though my implementation is quite a mess.

> Another problem with that is that ghostty's max_scrollback can only be set once at initialization, whereas our scrollback value is dynamic (which is why I'm currently using SB_MAX as the line count, which makes the performance issue even worse).

@noib3 can't you just delete from ghostty scrollback when it exceeds nvim scrollback?
